## 2. Why manual apply is needed

Postgres's `docker-entrypoint-initdb.d` mechanism **only runs on a fresh
database volume**. For existing deployments (DEV/UAT/PROD with accumulated
data), the new SQL files in `Dockerfile.postgres` would sit unused.

**Two paths to get the schema changes live:**

1. **Wipe + re-init** (simplest but destructive — loses solver_jobs and planner_output history):
   ```bash
   docker compose down -v   # removes the volume!
   docker compose up -d
   ```
   Not acceptable for UAT/PROD. Only safe for fresh DEV.

2. **Idempotent ALTER in live DB** (what this doc uses):
   ```bash
   docker exec -i <pg_container> psql -U <user> -d <db> < <migration.sql>
   ```
   Zero downtime. Uses `IF NOT EXISTS` / `ON CONFLICT` so safe to re-run.

